' Sequence Diagram 04 — Two-level slashing.
'
' Level 1: Equivocator A is detected and recorded.
' Level 2: Validator B *also* misbehaves by citing A's equivocating
'          block in its own justifications WITHOUT attaching a
'          SlashDeploy. B is detected as NeglectedInvalidBlock and
'          slashed in the same proposer round as A.
'
' This makes collusion mutually destructive: if B tries to cover for A,
' B goes down with A.
'
' Source of truth for Figure 8.1 in slashing-specification.md.
'
' Color palette: see Diagram 02 header for the legend.
'
' Render:
'   plantuml -tsvg docs/theory/slashing/diagrams/04-seq-two-level-slashing.puml

@startuml 04-seq-two-level-slashing
!theme plain

title Two-level slashing — collusion is mutually destructive

skinparam sequence {
  ArrowColor              #444444
  LifeLineBorderColor     #666666
  ParticipantBorderColor  #333333
  NoteBorderColor         #666666
  NoteBackgroundColor     #FFF8E1
  GroupBorderColor        #333333
  DividerBackgroundColor  #ECEFF1
}
skinparam defaultFontName "sans-serif"
skinparam defaultFontSize 11

autonumber

actor       "Equivocator A"          as A    #F8C3B8
actor       "Colluder B"             as Bact #F8C3B8
actor       "Honest Proposer P"      as P    #C8E6C9
participant "Validate"               as V    #FFECB3
participant "EquivocationDetector"   as D    #FFECB3
participant "MultiParentCasperImpl"  as C    #FFECB3
participant "BlockDagStorage"        as DS   #C8E6C9
participant "EquivocationTrackerStore" as T  #C8E6C9
participant "CasperSnapshot\n(in-memory snapshot of\nDAG + on-chain state\npre-loaded by block_processor)" as CS #C8E6C9
participant "BlockCreator"           as BC   #B2DFDB
participant "PoS Rholang"            as PoS  #D1C4E9
database    "Bond map\n(on-chain state)" as Bm  #D1C4E9

note over A, Bm #ECEFF1
  **Preconditions**
  • Validators A, B, P all bonded with stake > 0.
  • A signs b @ seqN, then b' @ seqN with b' ≠ b
    (b' becomes a dependency of some later block).
  • B is **aware** of A's equivocation (b' is in B's view of the DAG).
  • B will choose to cite b' in its own block b_B's justifications
    WITHOUT attaching a SlashDeploy targeting A — that is the
    "neglect" act that triggers Level 2.

  **Color legend**
  red = adversarial / regression  ·  orange = detection verdict / slash effect
  green = honest write / Valid    ·  blue = read query
  purple = Rholang invocation     ·  teal = block gossip   ·  gray = internal
end note

== Level 1 — A equivocates and is recorded ==

A -[#C62828]> V ++ : signed b' @ seqN\n(b @ seqN was signed earlier; both in DAG)
note over V
  requested_as_dependency = ⊤ is computed
  upstream by the block-processor and passed
  in as a parameter to check_equivocations —
  it is not queried from DS by the detector.
end note
V -[#1565C0]> D ++ : check_equivocations(b',\n  requested_as_dependency = ⊤, snapshot)
D -[#546E7A]> D   : extract creator_justification\nfrom b' (proto_util)
D -[#1565C0]> DS  : latest_message_hash(b'.sender) → hash(b)
D -[#546E7A]> D   : creator_justification(b') ≠ b.hash\n→ equivocation detected
D -[#E65100]-> V  : InvalidBlock::AdmissibleEquivocation
deactivate D
V -[#E65100]> C ++ : InvalidBlock::AdmissibleEquivocation
deactivate V
C -[#E65100]> T   : insert_equivocation_record(A, seqN − 1, ∅)
C -[#E65100]> DS  : insert(b', invalid = true)
deactivate C
note right of T
  Level 1 done: an EquivocationRecord
  for A exists. Anyone who now cites b'
  must accompany it with a SlashDeploy
  targeting A, or be slashed themselves.
end note

== Level 2 setup — B cites A's invalid block WITHOUT slashing ==

Bact -[#C62828]> V ++ : signed block b_B @ seqN_B\nwith b' ∈ b_B.justifications,\nNO SlashDeploy attached
V -[#1565C0]> CS  : casper_snapshot.dag.lookup(j.latestBlockHash)\nfor each j ∈ b_B.justifications;\nfilter where lookup.invalid = TRUE
CS -[#1565C0]-> V : invalidJustifications = { b' }
V -[#1565C0]> CS  : casper_snapshot.on_chain_state.bonds_map
CS -[#1565C0]-> V : bonds_map (A still has bond > 0\nfrom b_B's view of the chain)
V -[#546E7A]> V   : neglectedInvalidJustification\n  := exists j ∈ invalidJustifications\n     where bonds_map[j.validator] > 0\n  → TRUE (j.validator = A, bond > 0)
V -[#546E7A]> V   : has_slash_system_deploys(b_B)\n  := scan b_B.body.system_deploys (input field of b_B)\n     for SystemDeployData::Slash variant\n  → FALSE (B did not attach one)
V -[#546E7A]> V   : reject ⟺ neglected ∧ ¬has_slash\n  → REJECT (post-fix branch, see Diagram 08)
V -[#E65100]-> C ++ : InvalidBlock::NeglectedInvalidBlock
deactivate V
note right of V
  Source: validate.rs:989-1030
  (the post-fix Rust widening admits
  blocks that DO attach a slash; B
  did not, so b_B is rejected.)
end note

C -[#E65100]> T   : insert_equivocation_record(B, seqN_B − 1, ∅)
C -[#E65100]> DS  : insert(b_B, invalid = true)
deactivate C

== Honest proposer P slashes BOTH offenders in one round ==

P -[#00838F]> BC ++ : propose new block at seqM (seqM > max(seqN, seqN_B))
note over BC, CS
  prepare_slashing_deploys reads from the
  CasperSnapshot pre-loaded by the
  block-processor — NOT live DS calls.
end note
BC -[#1565C0]> CS  : casper_snapshot.dag.invalid_latest_messages()
CS -[#1565C0]-> BC : { (A, b'), (B, b_B) }
BC -[#1565C0]> T   : equivocation_records()
T -[#1565C0]-> BC  : { (A, seqN − 1, ∅), (B, seqN_B − 1, ∅) }
BC -[#1565C0]> CS  : casper_snapshot.on_chain_state.bonds_map
CS -[#1565C0]-> BC : bonds_map (both A and B still bonded)
BC -[#546E7A]> BC  : filter where bonds_map[*] > 0\n→ keep both A and B
note right of BC
  prepare_slashing_deploys
  emits ONE SlashDeploy per
  offender; both are bundled
  into the SAME block bP as
  separate system_deploys.
  They execute sequentially
  during local block evaluation
  but produce ONE post-state
  hash gossiped to the network.
end note
BC -[#6A1B9A]> PoS ++ : SlashDeploy(blockHash = b'.hash,\n  target = A) — system_deploys[0]
PoS -[#E65100]> Bm   : atomic stateUpdateCh!{\n  allBonds := allBonds[A := 0],\n  activeValidators := \\ {A},\n  committedRewards := \\ {A}\n} ; (true, Nil)\n(single map-construction step,\n PoS.rhox:473-482;\n A's bond transferred to Coop vault)
PoS -[#2E7D32]-> BC  : (true, Nil) on returnCh
BC -[#6A1B9A]> PoS   : SlashDeploy(blockHash = b_B.hash,\n  target = B) — system_deploys[1]
PoS -[#E65100]> Bm   : atomic stateUpdateCh!{\n  allBonds := allBonds[B := 0],\n  activeValidators := \\ {B},\n  committedRewards := \\ {B}\n} ; (true, Nil)\n(B's bond transferred to Coop vault)
PoS -[#2E7D32]-> BC -- : (true, Nil) on returnCh
deactivate BC

note over A, Bm #C8E6C9
  **Outcome**
  A and B are **both** slashed in the same block bP.
  Collusion is mutually destructive: if B had attached
  a SlashDeploy(b', A) to b_B, then b_B would have been
  ADMITTED (post-fix Rust widening, T-9.9), and only A
  would have been slashed. By neglecting, B incurs the
  same economic cost as the equivocator.
end note

@enduml
